We use a binary search approach to find the first bad version efficiently. We start with the first and last versions (1 and n) and repeatedly halve the search space until we find the first bad version. If we find a bad version, we discard the left half; otherwise, we discard the right half. This approach has a time complexity of O(log(n)) and requires only a constant amount of space, making it highly efficient for finding the first bad version.

